Mental Health Crisis Early-Warning System (MHCEWS): The MHCEWS generates\cb1  \cb3 ZIP-code-level weekly risk records, each uniquely identified by a composite\cb1  \cb3 key of zip_code + ISO 8601 week_start_date and described with rich metadata\cb1  \cb3 across four structured layers: Identity, Signal, Prediction, and Action,, which provides both human-readable field labels and machine-readable typed values\cb1  \cb3 so that any downstream system can interpret the data without additional\cb1  \cb3 context ('F'). Records are delivered via a REST API using standard HTTP\cb1  \cb3 protocols that are open, free, and universally implementable, with OAuth 2.0\cb1  \cb3 authentication for sensitive operational feeds such as real-time dispatch\cb1  \cb3 logs, while aggregate risk scores remain openly accessible ('A'). All field\cb1  \cb3 names follow snake_case conventions consistent with JSON-LD standards, and\cb1  \cb3 geographic identifiers use Census FIPS codes and ZCTA ZIP codes that are controlled\cb1  \cb3 vocabularies maintained by the U.S. Census Bureau to make records\cb1  \cb3 interpretable by any system that implements these widely adopted standards\cb1  \cb3 ('I'). Each record includes a provenance block containing data_source,\cb1  \cb3 model_version, and data_freshness timestamps for every contributing feed,\cb1  \cb3 and all public outputs are released under the Creative Commons Attribution\cb1  \cb3 4.0 license, ensuring that users can trace exactly which inputs produced a\cb1  \cb3 given risk score and understand the terms under which they may reuse it ('R').}